{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a4ed823-104b-4d49-9be8-ad7e3c7515a6","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling `File`/`Directory` directly. In tests, mock or stub the interface.\n\nAlternatively, the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package provides a pre-built `IFileSystem` abstraction with a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from maintaining your own wrapper:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\nUse whichever fits your project's complexity — a hand-rolled interface is fine for a few methods; the NuGet package shines when you touch many `System.IO` APIs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5c5e99af-b2ed-49b5-b88a-ae5e47b477d1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system calls testable in their .NET project. This is a general software engineering question about testability patterns, not a specific codebase task. I can answer this directly from knowledge.","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"4817:1EAA:85CF94:9A1396:69FBF251"},"id":"39434c93-c50a-4299-8334-5035e441b585","timestamp":"2026-05-07T02:00:59.396Z","parentId":"2f564e99-2956-4f3f-9a12-d6a730f107be"}
